GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
SESSION 2025
H 2
HOUSE BILL 437
Committee Substitute Favorable 4/8/25
Short Title: Establish Drug-Free Homeless Service Zones. (Public)
Sponsors:
Referred to:
March 19, 2025
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO ESTABLISH DRUG-FREE HOMELESS SERVICE ZONES AND INCREASE
3 THE PUNISHMENT IMPOSED FOR COMMITTING CERTAIN DRUG OFFENSES IN
4 A DRUG-FREE HOMELESS SERVICE ZONE.
5 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
6 SECTION 1. This act shall be known as "The Drug-Free Homeless Service Zones
7 Act."
8 SECTION 2. G.S. 90-95(e) reads as rewritten:
9 "(e) The prescribed punishment and degree of any offense under this Article shall be
10 subject to the following conditions, but the punishment for an offense may be increased only by
11 the maximum authorized under any one of the applicable conditions:
12 …
13 (8) Any person 21 years of age or older who commits an offense under
14 G.S. 90-95(a)(1) on property used for a child care center, or for an elementary
15 or secondary school or within 1,000 feet of the boundary of real property used
16 for a child care center, or for an elementary or secondary school shall be
17 punished as a Class E felon. For purposes of this subdivision, the transfer of
18 less than five grams of marijuana for no remuneration shall not constitute a
19 delivery in violation of G.S. 90-95(a)(1). For purposes of this subdivision, a
20 child care center is as defined in G.S. 110-86(3)a., and that is licensed by the
21 Secretary of the Department of Health and Human Services.
22 (8a) Any person who commits an offense under G.S. 90-95(a)(1) in a drug-free
23 homeless service zone is guilty of a Class E felony if the person knows or
24 reasonably should know that it is a drug-free homeless service zone. Any
25 operator of a facility-based service who intentionally allows a person to
26 commit an offense under G.S. 90-95(a)(1) in a drug-free homeless service
27 zone is guilty of a Class H felony. For purposes of this subdivision, the transfer
28 of less than five grams of marijuana for no remuneration shall not constitute a
29 delivery in violation of G.S. 90-95(a)(1). The following definitions apply in
30 this subdivision:
31 a. Drug-free homeless service zone. – The following areas related to a
32 facility-based service:
33 1. If the facility-based service does not provide the services
34 described in sub-sub-subdivision 2. of this sub-subdivision, the
35 exterior and interior of any building and any accompanying
36 grounds used by a facility-based service and the area within
*H437-v-2*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 100 feet of that building or its accompanying grounds, if at
2 least one sign is permanently affixed in a visible manner at the
3 exterior of the main entrance of the facility that identifies the
4 building and its accompanying grounds as a drug-free
5 homeless service zone. The presence of this sign shall raise a
6 presumption that the person committing the offense knows or
7 reasonably should know that it is a drug-free homeless service
8 zone.
9 2. If the facility-based service provides shelter or housing for
10 victims of domestic violence that may be endangered if the
11 purpose or location of the facility were to become known, the
12 interior of any building and any outdoor area that may only be
13 accessed by entering through the building used by a
14 facility-based service, if at least one sign is permanently
15 affixed in a visible manner inside the building and within 5 feet
16 of the main entrance of the facility that identifies the building
17 as a drug-free homeless service zone. The presence of this sign
18 shall raise a presumption that the person committing the
19 offense knows or reasonably should know that it is a drug-free
20 homeless service zone.
21 b. Facility-based service. – Any (i) emergency or temporary shelter,
22 transitional housing provider, or permanent supportive housing entity
23 that receives local, State, or federal funds for the purpose of providing
24 shelter to homeless persons or (ii) other entity or facility that receives
25 local, State, or federal funds and primarily provides treatment,
26 preventive care, or other services to homeless persons.
27 c. Operator. – A sole proprietorship, corporation, partnership, joint
28 venture, limited partnership, limited liability partnership, limited
29 liability company, or any other entity or business association, or
30 contractor or subcontractor of the same, that is the recipient of local,
31 State, or federal funds to use for the provision of a facility-based
32 service.
33 …."
34 SECTION 3. This act becomes effective December 1, 2025, and applies to offenses
35 committed on or after that date.
